<p><b>Mount Shasta</b> (<i>Úytaahkoo</i>, <a href="/wiki/Karuk_language" title="Karuk language">Karuk</a>) or the "White Mountain" in English, a 14,179-foot (4,322&#160;m)<sup id="cite_ref-NGS_0-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-NGS-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> <a href="/wiki/Stratovolcano" title="Stratovolcano">stratovolcano</a>, is the second-highest peak in the <a href="/wiki/Cascade_Range" title="Cascade Range">Cascade Range</a> and the <a href="/wiki/List_of_California_fourteeners" title="List of California fourteeners">fifth highest peak</a> in <a href="/wiki/California" title="California">California</a>. It is a member in the <a href="/wiki/Cascade_Volcanoes" title="Cascade Volcanoes">Cascade Volcanic Arc</a> and is located in <a href="/wiki/Siskiyou_County" title="Siskiyou County" class="mw-redirect">Siskiyou County</a>. Mount Shasta has an estimated volume of 108&#160;cubic miles (450&#160;km<sup>3</sup>), making it the most voluminous stratovolcano in the Cascades.<sup id="cite_ref-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-5" title=""><span>[</span>6<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>The mountain and its surrounding area are managed by the U.S. Forest Service, <a href="/wiki/Shasta-Trinity_National_Forest" title="Shasta-Trinity National Forest">Shasta-Trinity National Forest</a>.</p>
